T1  - Returns to scale in a highly regulated economy: evidence from Indian firms
AU  - Fikkert, Brian
AU  - Hasan, Rana
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 56
IS  - 1
SP  - 51
EP  - 79
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/06/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3878(98)00052-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304387898000522
KW  - Returns to scale
KW  - Regulation
KW  - Industrial policy
KW  - Economic reforms
AB  - This paper examines returns to scale for a panel of Indian manufacturing firms from 1976–1985, a period in which government regulations restricted firms' expansion. Observers have argued that these regulations led to unexploited scale economies in Indian firms, and our estimates lend limited support to this view. Although a large number of firms produce below the minimum efficient scale, average returns to scale for the various industries are not significantly different from one. Our estimates suggest that recent deregulation will not generate significant gains in scale efficiency unless expansion is heavily biased towards growth in the smaller firms.
